\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We consider the problem of building phylogenies from bulk sequence data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We will assume we have 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 samples from a patient with 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 SNVs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We will treat the samples as species and consider the presence/absence of
 SNVs as characters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We face two challenges:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Samples are mixtures of clones
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mutations may be loss due to CNVs
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Model assumptions
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We make the following assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Mutations originate at most once on the tree.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Mutations can be lost after they are acquired.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Mutations evolve independently i.e.
 our tree probability decomposes as the product of mutations.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We will assume that we cannot perfectly observe the presence/absence of
 mutations.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Our input data will then be probabilities.
 Exactly the probability an SNV is clonally present in a sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We need this because of sequence coverage and clonal mixtures.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Pre-processing
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Before constructing the tree we will need to compute the probability a mutation
 is clonally present.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{b}$
\end_inset

 denote the number of mutated copies, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 total number of copies, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 the tumour content and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 the sequencing error.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The probability of observing a read with the mutation is
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
r & = & \begin{cases}
\frac{c_{b}t}{2(1-t)+c_{t}t} & c_{b}>0\\
\epsilon & c_{b}=0
\end{cases}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Our allelic count data is modelled as Binomial and we obtain the probability
 of presence by summing all 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{b}>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We use CNV data as in module 2 to inform the copy number.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Tree probability
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We use a modified version of the pruning algorithm.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We need the modification because the assumption of single origin creates
 dependencies in the tree.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{l}$
\end_inset

 be the probability a mutation is lost along a branch, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(z_{i}=0|\cdot)$
\end_inset

 the probability a mutation is absent at node 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p(z_{j}=0|\cdot)$
\end_inset

 the probability it is present.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We will compute 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(i,\tau)$
\end_inset

, the probability the mutation is present at node i given all possible combinati
ons of losses on the sub-tree rooted at i.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Q(i,\tau) & = & \begin{cases}
\pi_{l}p(z_{i}=0|\cdot)+(1-\pi_{l})p(z_{i}=1|\cdot) & i\in L(\tau)\\
\pi_{l}\prod_{j\in L(i)}p(z_{j}=0|\cdot)+(1-\pi_{l})\prod_{j\in C(i)}Q(j,\tau) & i\notin L(\tau)
\end{cases}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Tree probability
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 be the node where a mutation originates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Then we have
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p(\mathbf{x}|\tau,w) & = & Q(w,\tau)\prod_{i\in L(\tau)\backslash L(w)}p(z_{i}=0|\cdot)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now we do not know 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, so we place a Uniform prior, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(w)$
\end_inset

, and marginalise.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p(\mathbf{x}|\tau) & = & \sum_{w\in V(\tau)}p(\mathbf{x}|\tau,w)p(w)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus far we have focused on a single mutation.
 The probability for all mutations is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p(X|\tau) & = & \prod_{n=1}^{N}p(\mathbf{x}_{n}|\tau)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Inference
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We assume the number of samples is small.
 In this case we can enumerate all trees and evaluate their probabilities
 to compute the MAP estimator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We also optimise the probability of loss on each tree.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This leads to MAP estimators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tau},\hat{\pi}_{l}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For more than 10 samples this approach is not practical.
 We would then need to turn to MCMC methods.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
